{
  "doc_id": "46317",
  "text": "Listeria monocytogenes has been recognized as a major foodborne pathogen since the outbreaks in California and Switzerland [CITATION_1] involving cheeses. L. monocytogenes has the ability to withstand various environmental conditions, such as low pH [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and salt concentration of up to 10% [CITATION_4] . It is, therefore, not surprising that Listeria organisms can survive in various kinds of fermented products such as cheeses [CITATION_5] . Moreover, they can resume growth during the ripening of surface-ripened soft and semihard cheeses as a result of a pH rise [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Thus, any studies on antagonistic systems that could prevent growth of this organism in cheese are of great interest.",
